1 1. Markov Chains

1.1 Animation of 4-state Markov chain

The following code creates animation of Markov chain with 4 states for a given matrix of transition probabilities.
Make sure you create the MC.Matrix with required transition probabilities before running this code.

library(animation)
lambda=5
oopt = ani.options(interval = .5, nmax = 25) ## set some options first
MC.Matrix<-rbind(
  From.Pos1=c(To.Pos1=0,To.Pos2=0,To.Pos3=0,To.Pos4=0), ## Create Transition Probabilities Matix
  From.Pos2=c(To.Pos1=0,To.Pos2=0,To.Pos3=0,To.Pos4=0),
  From.Pos3=c(To.Pos1=0,To.Pos2=0,To.Pos3=0,To.Pos4=0),
  From.Pos4=c(To.Pos1=0,To.Pos2=0,To.Pos3=0,To.Pos4=0))
Current.State<-2
From.To<-rep(Current.State,2)

my.Data<-as.matrix(t(c(0,2)))   ## use loop to create images one by one
for (i in 1:ani.options("nmax")) {
  From.To[1]<-Current.State
  From.To[2]<-sample(1:4,1,prob=MC.Matrix[From.To[1],])
  Current.State<-From.To[2]
  
  wait.next<-rexp(1,lambda)
  my.Data<-rbind(my.Data,c(my.Data[length(my.Data[,1]),1]+1,From.To[2]))
  plot(my.Data,type="s",xlim=c(1,25),ylim=c(0,4),xlab="Time",ylab="State",lwd=3)
  abline(h=1,col="red")
  abline(h=4,col="red")
  ani.pause(wait.next)    ## pause for a while ('interval')
  
}

ani.options(oopt)   ## restore the options
library(knitr)

2.1 Modeling of Cognitive Processes Literature

Gilles Dutilh, Eric-Jan Wagenmakers, Ingmar Visser, Han L. J. van der Maas, A Phase Transition Model for the Speed-Accuracy Trade-Off in Response Time Experiments, Cognitive Science 35 (2011) 211â250, 2010 Cognitive Science Society, Inc.

Ingmar Visser, Seven things to remember about hidden Markov models: A tutorial on Markovian models for time series, Journal of Mathematical Psychology, 55, (2011), 403â415

2.2 The Speed-Accuracy Trade-Off in Response Time Experiment

The description of the problem below is from the article by Ingmar Visser.

The data are from consecutive lexical decision trials, in which the participant had to decide whether the presented sequence of letters formed a word or not.
The data that are analyzed here are from participant A in Experiment 1 in the article by Dutilh etal.
Each trial resulted in recording of response time and accuracy of answers.
To manipulate the accuracy and response times, there was a dynamic pay-off for accuracy of answers.
The pay-off for speed was determined as 1 minus the pay-off for accuracy.
The pay-off for accuracy was varied continuously in a zigzag manner, and there were 6 maxima for the pay-off for accuracy during 168 trials.

The participant was shown the reward after each trial, so that it affected behavior in future trial.
The response times(RT), accuracy (ACC), and the pay-off for accuracy (Pacc) are in the corresponding columns of the data.

The most striking feature of these data, and in particular the response times, is their seemingly periodic nature, and the goal of modeling is to capture this feature.
The periodicity of the data is clearly related to the pay-off for speed and accuracy, as shown by the correlations between the variables.

The key question about these data is what effect the (continuous) changes in pay-off for speed and accuracy have on the results of the experiment.

  • The first hypothesis states that continuous changes in pay-off should result in continuous changes in speed and accuracy.

  • Alternatively, the second hypothesis states that the changes in pay-off may result in switching between two modes of responding: one slow and accurate, and another with fast responses and accuracy at chance level.
    Hence, the second hypothesis states that continuous changes in pay-off should result in discontinuous changes in speed and accuracy.

In order to test the hypotheses above, the following models need to be compared:

  1. a 1-state model with the pay-off for accuracy as a predictor for response time and accuracy;
  2. a 2-state model with switching between the states.

The 2-state model can be further elaborated by making the transition probabilities depend on the pay-off for accuracy.

Note that the 1-state model is not a proper hidden Markov model because it has only a single state, which is, as a consequence not hidden, and moreover there is no dynamic part in the model because the transition matrix consists only of a single element equal to 1.

The 1-state model is in effect a multiple regression model for the response time and accuracy and it is specified by the following equations:

RTt=Î¼+Î²Pacct+Ïµt,RTt=Î¼+Î²Pacct+Ïµt,
with ÏµtÏµt distributed as Norm(0,Ï2)Norm(0,Ï2) ACCtACCt is a Bernoulli variable with probability of success pt,pt,, with
logit(pt)=b0+b1Pacctlogit(pt)=b0+b1Pacct
.

Here RTtRTt are the response times and ACCtACCt are the accuracy values; PacctPacct represents the pay-off for accuracy, scaled from 0 to 1, with 1 representing the maximum reward for accuracy, and no reward for speed; conversely, Pacct=0Pacct=0 means no reward for accuracy, and maximum reward for speed.

For the RT variable, the parameters of the model are: the mean response time Î¼Î¼, the regression coefficient Î²Î² relating the pay-off for accuracy to response time, and the standard deviation ÏÏ.
For the ACC variable, the parameters of the model are the coefficients b0b0 and b1b1, where b1b1 relates PacctPacct to the logit of the probability

P(ACCt=1)=pt.P(ACCt=1)=pt.

The second hypothesis states that there are two modes of behavior, and that the participant switches between these over the series of trials.
Such a hypothesis is naturally captured by a 2-state HMM.

The 2-state HMM is defined by the state dependent means and standard deviations of the RT variable and the state dependent probabilities for the ACC variable, i.e., P(ACCt=1)P(ACCt=1), as follows:

RTt=Î¼i+Ïµt,RTt=Î¼i+Ïµt,
with ÏµÏµ distributed as normal with mean 0 and std. Ï2iÏi2, i=1,2i=1,2.

ACCtACCt is distributed as Bernoulli(pi),i=1,2Bernoulli(pi),i=1,2.

For modeling RT then, the parameters of this model are the state dependent means Î¼iÎ¼i and standard deviations ÏiÏi.

For ACC, the parameters are the state dependent Bernoulli probabilities pipi.

After defining states with these parameters, estimate transition matrix A and the initial state probability vector ÏÏ.
Note that the variable Pacc has no role in the 2-state model described here.

In the 1-state model, the assumption is that Pacc influences response times and accuracy directly.

In the 2-state model, the core assumption is that there are two modes of behavior, slow and accurate versus fast guessing behavior, and that switching between these modes of behavior is influenced by the pay-off for accuracy.

Hence, Pacc is hypothesized to have an indirect influence on RT and ACC through the state variables.
This hypothesis can also be expressed within the framework of hidden Markov models by including Pacc as a covariate on the transition probabilities. That is, the transition probabilities are modeled as a function of Pacc.
The third model that is fitted to the data incorporates this idea.

The measurement equations, i.e., the equations that relate the hidden states to the observed variables, of the third model are identical to those of the 2-state model."

2.3.1 One-State Model for Response Time

Fit the one component model

RTt=Î¼+Ïµt,Ïµtâ¼N(0,Ï2).RTt=Î¼+Ïµt,Ïµtâ¼N(0,Ï2).

First, create the mix model using mix().

The fundamental assumption of a dependent mixture model is that at any time point, the observations are distributed as a mixture with nn components (or states), and that time-dependencies between the observations are due to time-dependencies between the mixture components (i.e., transition probabilities between the components).
These latter dependencies are assumed to follow a first-order Markov process: dependence of futures state on k=1k=1 previous states.
In the models we are considering here, the mixture distributions, the initial mixture probabilities and transition probabilities can all depend on covariates ztzt.

Then fit the mix model.

set.seed(6)
m1 <- mix(RT~1,nstates=1, data=sp1)
(fm1 <- fit(m1))
## iteration 0 logLik: -114.6113 
## converged at iteration 1 with logLik: -114.6113
## Convergence info: Log likelihood converged to within tol. (relative change) 
## 'log Lik.' -114.6113 (df=2)
## AIC:  233.2225 
## BIC:  239.4705

Take a note of the goodness of fit characteristics AIC and BIC. Check the summary.

summary.fm1<-summary(fm1)
## Mixture probabilities model 
## pr1 
##   1 
## 
## Response parameters 
## Resp 1 : gaussian 
##     Re1.(Intercept)    Re1.sd
## St1        6.035737 0.4786773

Since 1-state model is not really an HMM the summary only gives us the mean and the standard deviation of the variable RT.

Plot the histogram again with the distribution of the single state of the estimated model.

plot(speed.rt.hist,freq=FALSE)
lines(speed.rt.hist$mids,dnorm(speed.rt.hist$mids,summary.fm1[1],summary.fm1[2]))

2.3.5 Two-State Model for Both Accuracy and Response Time, No Predictors, Transition Probabilities Dependent on Payoff

Fit a model with intercepts only for Gaussian RT and multinomial ACC, making transition probabilities dependent on Pacc:

State 1:
RTt=Î¼1+Ïµt,1, Ïµt,1â¼N(0,Ï21);RTt=Î¼1+Ïµt,1, Ïµt,1â¼N(0,Ï12);
ACCtâ¼Binomial(p1);ACCtâ¼Binomial(p1);
State 2:
RTt=Î¼2+Ïµt,2, Ïµt,2â¼N(0,Ï22);RTt=Î¼2+Ïµt,2, Ïµt,2â¼N(0,Ï22);
ACCtâ¼Binomial(p2).ACCtâ¼Binomial(p2).
Dependence of transition probabilities is described by logistic regressions:

logit(1âa1,1(t))=Î²1,0+Î²1,1Pacct,logit(1âa1,1(t))=Î²1,0+Î²1,1Pacct,

logit(a2,2(t))=Î²2,0+Î²2,1Pacct,logit(a2,2(t))=Î²2,0+Î²2,1Pacct,

where ai,jai,j is the transition probability from state ii to state jj.
If the model has more than 2 states then logistic regression model will be replaced with multinomial logistic regression.

set.seed(1)
m2a <- depmix(list(RT~1,ACC~1),nstates=2, data=sp1,family=list(gaussian(),multinomial()),transition=~Pacc)

The parameters of this model are:

probability for Acc can be calculated from the odds ratio 0.285649 as

The parameters relating to the measurement part of the model fm2a are very similar to the parameters of the 2-state model fm2 without covariate effect on the transition probabilities.

The parameters of most interest for this model are the transition model parameters.

The best model explaining the data shows jumps between two states: Fast and wrong response, long and correct response.

3.2.2 Estimating transition probabilities for given states

After defining the states of the Markov Model we need to estimate the matrix of transition probabilities from the sequence of transitions.

Use markovchainFit from package markovchain

library(markovchain)

Create character names of the states using the classification sequence speed.rt.Pacc.som$unit.classif generated by SOM speed.rt.Pacc.som with two states: guessing mode GM and slow correct mode SCM.

speed.States<-rep(NA,length(speed[,1]))
speed.States[speed.rt.Pacc.som$unit.classif==1]<-"GM"
speed.States[speed.rt.Pacc.som$unit.classif==2]<-"SCM"

Estimate transition probabilities
